-- Milan FTSE MIB Stock Index Falls; Fiat, Telecom Italia, UniCredit Decline
-- Adam Ewing
-- 2010-06-24T15:57:15Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2010-06-24/fiat-pirelli-and-unicredit-shares-are-active-as-milan-index-declines.html

          
          
             Italy’s benchmark  FTSE MIB Index 
retreated 416.53, or 2.1 percent, to 19,942.39 in Milan, sliding
the most since June 4.  
 The following stocks are among the most active on the
Italian market today.  
 Fiat SpA  (F IM) fell for a third day, declining 2.6 percent
to 9.08 euros. The Italian carmaker may cut investments or
create a new company to manage its Pomigliano car factory, Il
Sole 24 Ore reported, without saying where it got the
information.  
 Intesa Sanpaolo SpA  (ISP IM) dropped 3 percent to 2.25
euros, falling for the fourth day. Italy’s second-biggest bank
agrees with stress tests on banks as long as the criteria used
is similar for all institutions, Chief Executive Officer  Corrado Passera  said at a seminar in Madrid today.  
 Telecom Italia SpA  (TIT IM), Italy’s biggest phone company,
slipped 2.4 percent to 0.938 euros, its third loss. The company
is being probed for abuse of its dominant position by Italy’s
antitrust regulator, according to a statement on the watchdog’s
website today.  
 UniCredit SpA  (UCG IM) fell for a third day, sliding 0.3
percent to 1.905 euros. Aabar Investments Chief Executive
Officer  Mohamed Badawy Al-Husseiny  said today the Abu Dhabi-
based fund acquired a 4.99 percent stake in UniCredit SpA,
Italy’s biggest bank.  
